Non-access modifiers do not control visibility. Instead, they control behavior, inheritance, instantiation, and special semantics of a class.

1. final Class -> A final class cannot be inherited (no subclassing).
Example: 
final class PaymentProcessor {
    public void process() {
        System.out.println("Processing payment");
    }
}
This is invalid:
class OnlinePayment extends PaymentProcessor { } // Compile-time error

2. abstract Class -> Cannot be instantiated, may contain abstract methods (methods without body), used as a base class.
Example:
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void move();

    void fuelType() {
        System.out.println("Petrol or Diesel");
    }
}
Subclass implementation:
class Car extends Vehicle {
    void move() {
        System.out.println("Car moves on roads");
    }
}

*final vs abstract
These cannot be used together:
final abstract class Example { } // Invalid

Why?
abstract → needs subclassing
final → forbids subclassing
